. The principal work of Panaetius was his treatise on the theory of moral obligatron (περὶτοῦ καθήκοντος) in three books, eomposed thirty years before his death (de off. 11158). In this he proposed to investigate firstly what was moral (honestum) or immoral (turpe), then what was expedient (utile), or not expedient (inutile), and lastly how the apparent conflict between the honestum and utile was to be decided. The third subject of enquiry he had not completed, and it was left to Cicero, who in the first two books borrowed from Panaetius without any essential alteration, to deal with it independently and without assistance (de off. 111 c, 115 7 ἦ, ad Art. XVI 11, 4 τὰ περὶ rob καθήκοντος, quatenus Panaetius, absolvi duobus: tres surrt illius, sed cum initio divisisset ito, tria genero exquirendi officii esse-de duobus primis praeclare dis· seruit, de tertio pollicetur se deinceps, sed nihil scripsit. Cicero was induced to follow Panaetius not merely because of the superiority- of his work in other respects, but because he endeavoured to exhibit the philosophy ol morals in its practical application to life, laying aside abstract in· vestigations and paradoxical definitions (de off. 11 5 35), and modifying the severity which characterised the older school ol Stoics (defin. lv 5 79 quam illorum (Stoicoruml tristitiam atque asperitatem fugiens Pa· naetius nce acerbitatem sententiarum nec disserendi spinas probavit ficitque in altero genere mitior, in altero illustrior, semperque habuit in ore Platonem, Aristotelem, Xenocratem, Theophrastum, Dicaearchum, ut ipsius scripta declarant: de leg. 111 5 141³. ain tandem? etiam a Stoicis ista tractata sunt (sc. de magistratibusli M. non sanc nisi a Dione Stoico, et postea a magno homine et in primis erudito, Panaetio: nam veteres verbotenus, acute illi quidem, sed non acl hunc nsum popularem atque civilem de rep. disserebant.
